originalText.text: This facility is more concerned about making a pretty penny than actually helping their patients and giving them the best, healthiest option possible. I came for a consultation due to a past injury leaving my front tooth chipped. I came to find out, from the doctor assigned to me, that my bite was too tight to add any length to my chipped tooth. She then proceeded to pressure me into getting porcelain veneers. The only problem was she would have to shave down half my tooth structure, which didn‚Äôt seem like a great option to me in my mind, considering I‚Äôm only 22 and my teeth are healthy besides the chip. She used nasty sales tactics such as belittling and criticizing my appearance in hopes of making money off of my insecurities (which I acknowledge is unfortunately common in the cosmetic industry). I‚Äôm an actress and she told me i would look extremely better on camera with this adjustment, among other comments of my appearance. She not only commented on my teeth but also commented on the structure of my jaw, and bone structure. She was then trying to convince me to get a whole mouth full of veneers, rather than just fixing the single tooth (which if you know about the expenses of veneers, you could imagine the financial difference). Luckily I‚Äôm a very confident women, and immediately saw this as a sleazy sales pitch, but my heart went out to those who would have fallen victim to this manipulation. When I asked her if I could get Invisalign or a retainer to fix the problem in my bite, preventing me from taking my tooth structure off, she told me no and that the only thing that could fix this would be braces for a year. I left this facility and went to get a second opinion. At this second doctors office I was given astronomically different advice. This new doctor approached me with compassion and kindness. She told me I had a beautiful smile and that I was a beautiful young women. She advised me to get Invisalign to solve the problem of my bite because she didn‚Äôt want to take off anything from my teeth, as they‚Äôre very healthy. I‚Äôve just begun the Invisalign process which will take a little longer than 6 months (not a year). All of this is to say, I do not recommend this facility. Their doctors are rude, money hungry, and ruthless.

originalText.text:
After consulting with a few cosmetic dentists, I decided on Dr Kantor, who was also highly recommended by my dermatologist, for my porcelain veneers. I liked that he has over 15 years of experience as a cosmetic dentist, performed thousands of porcelain veneer cases and was very impressed by his patient portfolio photos. I had cosmetic issues that were causing me not to smile: chipped front tooth, gap between my front two teeth, crooked bottom teeth, a crossbite, worn and yellow teeth. My teeth hardly showed when speaking. People would tell me that my teeth didn‚Äôt match my face. Dr. Kantor explained to me that all my issues would be corrected with porcelain veneers without having to get braces or invisalign. He showed me during the consult how I would look by doing a mockup with dental resin. After three visits (including the consult) I now have my beautiful permanent porcelain veneers which look better than I ever imagined. The color, the bite, the size are perfect. The crooked bottom teeth are now straight, my gap is gone, and I have a more youthful, bigger brighter smile while still looking very natural. I was even given retainers to prevent my teeth from shifting. Jason Kim, the ceramist, is a master working exclusively with LLK. His assistant, Marguerita, was very professional and caring. Yvonne, the office manager, was such a pleasure and made sure my experience went well. Dr Kantor is an artist and gifted cosmetic surgeon who listened to me and delivered on everything he promised. He is also a really nice guy and called me the day after my procedure to see how I was doing. Thank you!

LIZABETH ZELDENRUST
